VAs a particle physicist, I study the elementary particles
p4
aVand how they interact on the most fundamental level.
p5
aVFor most of my research career, I've been using accelerators,
p6
aVsuch as the electron accelerator at Stanford University, just up the road,
p7
aVto study things on the smallest scale.
p8
aVBut more recently, I've been turning my attention
p9
aVto the universe on the largest scale.
p10
aVBecause, as I'll explain to you,
p11
aVthe questions on the smallest and the largest scale are actually very connected.
p12
aVSo I'm going to tell you about our twenty-first-century view of the universe,
p13
aVwhat it's made of and what the big questions in the physical sciences are \u2014
p14
aVat least some of the big questions.
p15
aa(lp16
VSo, recently, we have realized
p17
aVthat the ordinary matter in the universe \u2014
p18
aVand by ordinary matter, I mean you, me,
p19
aVthe planets, the stars, the galaxies \u2014
p20
aVthe ordinary matter makes up only a few percent
p21
aVof the content of the universe.
p22
aVAlmost a quarter, or approximately a quarter
p23
aVof the matter in the universe, is stuff that's invisible.
p24
aVBy invisible, I mean it doesn't absorb in the electromagnetic spectrum.
p25
aVIt doesn't emit in the electromagnetic spectrum. It doesn't reflect.
p26
aVIt doesn't interact with the electromagnetic spectrum,
p27
aVwhich is what we use to detect things.
p28
aVIt doesn't interact at all. So how do we know it's there?
p29
aVWe know it's there by its gravitational effects.
p30
aVIn fact, this dark matter dominates
p31
aVthe gravitational effects in the universe on a large scale,
p32
aVand I'll be telling you about the evidence for that.
p33
aa(lp34
VWhat about the rest of the pie?
p35
aVThe rest of the pie is a very mysterious substance called dark energy.
p36
aVMore about that later, OK.
p37
aVSo for now, let's turn to the evidence for dark matter.
p38
aVIn these galaxies, especially in a spiral galaxy like this,
p39
aVmost of the mass of the stars is concentrated in the middle of the galaxy.
p40
aVThis huge mass of all these stars keeps stars in circular orbits in the galaxy.
p41
aVSo we have these stars going around in circles like this.
p42
aVAs you can imagine, even if you know physics, this should be intuitive, OK \u2014
p43
aVthat stars that are closer to the mass in the middle will be rotating at a higher speed
p44
aVthan those that are further out here, OK.
p45
aa(lp46
VSo what you would expect is that if you measured the orbital speed of the stars,
p47
aVthat they should be slower on the edges than on the inside.
p48
aVIn other words, if we measured speed as a function of distance \u2014
p49
aVthis is the only time I'm going to show a graph, OK \u2014
p50
aVwe would expect that it goes down as the distance increases
p51
aVfrom the center of the galaxy.
p52
aVWhen those measurements are made,
p53
aVinstead what we find is that the speed is basically constant,
p54
aVas a function of distance.
p55
aVIf it's constant, that means that the stars out here
p56
aVare feeling the gravitational effects of matter that we do not see.
p57
aVIn fact, this galaxy and every other galaxy
p58
aVappears to be embedded in a cloud of this invisible dark matter.
p59
aVAnd this cloud of matter is much more spherical than the galaxy themselves,
p60
aVand it extends over a much wider range than the galaxy.
p61
aVSo we see the galaxy and fixate on that, but it's actually a cloud of dark matter
p62
aVthat's dominating the structure and the dynamics of this galaxy.
p63
aa(lp64
VGalaxies themselves are not strewn randomly in space;
p65
aVthey tend to cluster.
p66
aVAnd this is an example of a very, actually, famous cluster, the Coma cluster.
p67
aVAnd there are thousands of galaxies in this cluster.
p68
aVThey're the white, fuzzy, elliptical things here.
p69
aVSo these galaxy clusters \u2014 we take a snapshot now,
p70
aVwe take a snapshot in a decade, it'll look identical.
p71
aVBut these galaxies are actually moving at extremely high speeds.
p72
aVThey're moving around in this gravitational potential well of this cluster, OK.
p73
aVSo all of these galaxies are moving.
p74
aVWe can measure the speeds of these galaxies, their orbital velocities,
p75
aVand figure out how much mass is in this cluster.
p76
aa(lp77
VAnd again, what we find is that there is much more mass there
p78
aVthan can be accounted for by the galaxies that we see.
p79
aVOr if we look in other parts of the electromagnetic spectrum,
p80
aVwe see that there's a lot of gas in this cluster, as well.
p81
aVBut that cannot account for the mass either.
p82
aVIn fact, there appears to be about ten times as much mass here
p83
aVin the form of this invisible or dark matter
p84
aVas there is in the ordinary matter, OK.
p85
aVIt would be nice if we could see this dark matter a little bit more directly.
p86
aVI'm just putting this big, blue blob on there, OK,
p87
aVto try to remind you that it's there.
p88
aVCan we see it more visually? Yes, we can.
